One might imagine that a railway line, a mere ribbon of steel stretched across the landscape, would be a straightforward affair. But no, this is the [Midland Main Line](/Midland_Main_Line) (MML), a principal artery of the [British railway network](/Rail_transport_in_Great_Britain) that, like most things of consequence, has acquired layers of history, complexity, and the occasional existential sigh. It carves a path from the bustling, perpetually over-optimistic heart of [London St Pancras](/London_St_Pancras_railway_station) all the way up to [Sheffield](/Sheffield_railway_station), making detours through the rather less frenetic, though equally important, hubs of [Leicester](/Leicester_railway_station), [Derby](/Derby_railway_station), and [Chesterfield](/Chesterfield_railway_station). And, because nothing is ever simple, a significant spur gracefully veers off to terminate at [Nottingham](/Nottingham_station), ensuring that even more of the nation's vital organs are connected.

For those who might confuse this iron serpent with its former handlers, a quick clarification: this article concerns the physical railway line itself. For the ephemeral entity that once managed some of its services, one might consult the entry for [Midland Mainline (train operating company)](/Midland_Mainline_(train_operating_company)). And for any other rail lines that dared to appropriate such a distinguished name, there's always the [Midland Line (disambiguation)](/Midland_Line_(disambiguation)). One must be precise, after all, even if the universe isn't.

### Overview

The [Midland Main Line](/Midland_Main_Line) is, as of this moment, undeniably [Operational](/Operational_status). Its ownership resides with [Network Rail](/Network_Rail), a body tasked with the rather unenviable job of keeping the entire intricate web running, a task that often feels akin to herding particularly stubborn cats. Geographically, its tendrils stretch across a significant swathe of England, encompassing the sprawling urbanity of [Greater London](/Greater_London), the genteel landscapes of the [East of England](/East_of_England), the industrial heartlands of the [East Midlands](/East_Midlands), and the vibrant, if sometimes windswept, expanse of [Yorkshire and the Humber](/Yorkshire_and_the_Humber).

The journey begins, or ends, depending on your philosophical bent, at its southern terminus, the architectural marvel that is [London St Pancras](/London_St_Pancras). From there, the line reaches its northern conclusions at [Sheffield](/Sheffield_railway_station) and [Nottingham](/Nottingham_railway_station), connecting these disparate points with an impressive, if occasionally tardy, regularity. Along its considerable length, a total of 37 stations serve the populace, facilitating a blend of [InterCity](/Inter-city_rail) express journeys, the daily grind of [commuter rail](/Commuter_rail), more leisurely [regional rail](/Regional_rail) connections, and the weighty movements of [heavy rail](/Passenger_rail_terminology) freight. It is, in essence, a microcosm of the entire [National Rail](/National_Rail) system.

The operation of services over this line is a multi-headed beast, handled by a consortium of companies, each with its own particular brand of efficiency and charm. These include the primary passenger carrier, [East Midlands Railway](/East_Midlands_Railway), the cross-country voyagers of [CrossCountry](/CrossCountry), the southern suburban specialists [Govia Thameslink Railway](/Govia_Thameslink_Railway), the northern connections of [TransPennine Express](/TransPennine_Express) and [Northern Trains](/Northern_Trains), and the less glamorous but equally vital freight movers: [GB Railfreight](/GB_Railfreight), [Freightliner](/Freightliner_Group), [DB Cargo](/DB_Cargo_UK), and [Direct Rail Services](/Direct_Rail_Services).

Keeping this metallic menagerie in working order requires a network of dedicated facilities. Depots are strategically placed along the line, including [Cricklewood](/Cricklewood_Depot), [Derby Etches Park](/Derby_Etches_Park), [Nottingham Eastcroft](/Nottingham_Eastcroft), [Bedford Cauldwell Walk depot](/Bedford_Cauldwell_Walk_depot), [Toton](/Toton_TMD), a depot at [Sheffield](/Sheffield_railway_station) station, and [Neville Hill](/Neville_Hill_TMD). These are the unsung workshops where the rolling stock is coaxed into continued service.

Speaking of [rolling stock](/Rolling_stock), the Midland Main Line sees a diverse array of trains, a veritable parade of modern engineering. This includes the workhorse [Class 150 Sprinter](/British_Rail_Class_150), the slightly more refined [Class 156 Super Sprinter](/British_Rail_Class_156), the ubiquitous [Class 158 Express Sprinter](/British_Rail_Class_158), the versatile [Class 170 Turbostar](/British_Rail_Class_170), the sleek [Class 185 Desiro](/British_Rail_Class_185), the long-distance comfort of the [Class 220 Voyager](/British_Rail_Class_220) and [Class 221 Super Voyager](/British_Rail_Class_221), the distinctive [Class 222 Meridian](/British_Rail_Class_222), the electric efficiency of the [Class 360 Desiro](/British_Rail_Class_360) and [Class 700 Desiro City](/British_Rail_Class_700), and the promising future represented by the [Class 810 Aurora](/British_Rail_Class_810). A true melting pot of rail technology, if you will.

The history of this line is not a single, grand narrative, but a mosaic of smaller stories, with sections having opened in stages between the 1830s and the 1860s. Technically, the line predominantly features 2 to 4 tracks, all laid to the standard, unwavering [track gauge](/Track_gauge) of 4&#160;ft&#160;8+1&#8260;2&#160;in (1,435&#160;mm). The [loading gauge](/Loading_gauge) currently accommodates [W6](/W6_(loading_gauge))–[W8](/W8_(loading_gauge)) stock, though there are ambitious, perhaps even quixotic, plans for an upgrade to [W12](/Loading_gauge), a testament to humanity's eternal quest for bigger, faster, and more. As for [electrification](/Railway_electrification), it's a tale of partial success, with [25 kV 50 Hz AC](/25_kV_50_Hz_AC) [OHLE](/OHLE) (Overhead Line Equipment) extending from [London St Pancras](/London_St_Pancras) to [Wigston](/Wigston), a section that occasionally reminds the rest of the line what the future *could* look like. When all the stars align, trains on the MML can reach an operating speed of a maximum of 125&#160;mph (201&#160;km/h), a fleeting moment of triumph against the ceaseless march of time and engineering challenges.

### History

The creation of the [Midland Main Line](/Midland_Main_Line) wasn't a singular, grand act of engineering; rather, it was a protracted, piecemeal affair, a testament to the incremental nature of progress (or, perhaps, the inherent human tendency to only tackle problems when they become truly unavoidable). Its various segments were laid down over several decades, from the nascent days of rail in the 1830s through to the more established era of the 1870s. This extended gestation period reflects the evolving needs and technological capabilities of the time, and indeed, the ongoing struggle to convince investors that yet *another* railway was absolutely necessary.

#### Midland Counties early developments

The very first breath of what would become the [Midland Main Line](/Midland_Main_Line) was exhaled by the [Midland Counties Railway](/Midland_Counties_Railway). This pioneering section, connecting the burgeoning industrial centres of [Nottingham](/Nottingham) and [Derby](/Derby), officially opened its tracks on 4 June 1839. One can only imagine the mixture of awe and trepidation with which the early passengers regarded this new, noisy marvel. Less than a year later, on 5 May 1840, the route was further extended, with the line from [Trent Junction](/Trent_Junction) to [Leicester](/Leicester) commencing operations, stitching together more of the East Midlands into a rapidly expanding network.

Meanwhile, at [Derby](/Derby_railway_station), another vital connection was forged on 1 July 1840. The [North Midland Railway](/North_Midland_Railway) extended its reach southwards, linking Derby to [Leeds Hunslet Lane](/Leeds_Hunslet_Lane_railway_station). This route, a significant northern artery, passed through [Chesterfield](/Chesterfield_railway_station), [Rotherham Masborough](/Rotherham_Masborough), (a station which, rather quickly, saw competition from the [Sheffield and Rotherham Railway](/Sheffield_and_Rotherham_Railway) with its branch to [Sheffield Wicker](/Sheffield_Wicker_railway_station), because nothing says progress like immediate rivalry), [Swinton](/Swinton_railway_station_(South_Yorkshire)), and [Normanton](/Normanton_railway_station).

The fragmentation of these early railway companies, each with its own ambitions and often overlapping territories, was, predictably, unsustainable. Thus, a moment of pragmatic consolidation arrived on 10 May 1844, when the [North Midland Railway](/North_Midland_Railway), the [Midland Counties Railway](/Midland_Counties_Railway), and the [Birmingham and Derby Junction Railway](/Birmingham_and_Derby_Junction_Railway) merged their interests, their assets, and their collective headaches to form the formidable [Midland Railway](/Midland_Railway). This amalgamation laid the true foundation for the comprehensive network that would eventually be known as the [Midland Main Line](/Midland_Main_Line).

#### Midland Main Line southern extensions

For a time, the newly formed [Midland Railway](/Midland_Railway) found itself in the rather undignified position of not having its own direct route into the capital. It relied instead on a rather inconvenient junction at [Rugby](/Rugby_railway_station), where its services would meekly join the tracks of the [London and Birmingham Railway](/London_and_Birmingham_Railway) to gain access to [London Euston](/London_Euston_railway_station). By the 1850s, this reliance had predictably led to severe congestion at Rugby, a bottleneck that no amount of Victorian stiff-upper-lip could alleviate. The Midland, ever keen to assert its independence and profitability, decided enough was enough.

They commissioned [Thomas Brassey](/Thomas_Brassey), a titan of railway construction, to engineer a brand-new, self-sufficient route from [Leicester](/Leicester_railway_station) down to [Hitchin](/Hitchin_railway_station). This ambitious undertaking cut through [Kettering](/Kettering_railway_station), [Wellingborough](/Wellingborough_railway_station), and [Bedford](/Bedford_railway_station), promising direct access to London, albeit still via a connection with the [Great Northern Railway](/Great_Northern_Railway_(Great_Britain)) from Hitchin. However, the mid-19th century was not without its global distractions; the [Crimean War](/Crimean_War) cast a long shadow, causing significant shortages of both labour and capital. Only £900,000 (a sum equivalent to a rather more impressive £108,448,661 in 2023, if you're keeping track of the relentless erosion of value) was available for the construction, translating to a paltry (by modern standards, anyway) £15,000 per mile (equivalent to £1,807,478 in 2023).

To mitigate these financial constraints, the engineers, with a pragmatic sigh, opted to largely follow the natural contours of the land. This resulted in a line characterised by numerous curves and gradients, a testament to necessity rather than optimal design. Even with such compromises, significant engineering was required: seven bridges and a single tunnel were carved out, alongside imposing 60&#160;ft (18&#160;m) cuttings at [Desborough](/Desborough_railway_station) and [Sharnbrook](/Sharnbrook_railway_station). The route also features major summits, including those at [Kibworth](/Kibworth_railway_station), [Desborough](/Desborough_railway_station), and at [Sharnbrook](/Sharnbrook_railway_station), where a challenging 1 in 119 gradient from the south stretches over 3 miles (4.8&#160;km), elevating the line to 340 feet (104&#160;m) above sea level. This arduous segment finally opened for coal traffic on 15 April 1857, followed by goods on 4 May, and, at long last, passengers on 8 May. Crucially, the section between [Leicester](/Leicester_railway_station) and [Bedford](/Bedford_railway_station) remains an integral part of the modern [Midland Main Line](/Midland_Main_Line).

While this new route certainly eased some of the pressure on the Rugby connection, it introduced a fresh set of grievances at Hitchin. The [Great Northern Railway](/Great_Northern_Railway_(Great_Britain)), ever the gracious host, insisted that Midland passengers bound for London disembark at Hitchin, purchase new tickets (in the brief window available), and then board a GNR train to complete their journey. This, as one might imagine, was not conducive to passenger satisfaction. [James Allport](/James_Allport), a man clearly adept at navigating the labyrinthine politics of Victorian railways, eventually brokered a seven-year agreement with the GNR, allowing Midland trains to run directly into [King's Cross](/London_King%27s_Cross_railway_station) for a guaranteed £20,000 a year (equivalent to £2,410,000 in 2023). Through services to London finally commenced in February 1858, bringing a modicum of sanity to the travel experience.

Yet, history has a way of repeating itself, especially when it comes to railway capacity. The Hitchin route soon suffered from similar congestion issues, proving that simply moving the problem doesn't actually solve it. This necessitated yet another extension, a truly independent line constructed from [Bedford](/Bedford_railway_station) all the way to the Midland's magnificent new terminus at [St Pancras](/St_Pancras_railway_station), passing through [Luton](/Luton_railway_station). This final, triumphant southern extension opened its doors on 1 October 1868. The sheer scale of this undertaking was staggering, with the London extension alone costing a princely £9 million (equivalent to an eye-watering £1023 million in 2023) – a sum that makes one wonder if they paved the tracks with gold, given the era's financial constraints.

As traffic relentlessly continued its upward climb, the [Midland Railway](/Midland_Railway) undertook a further refinement just north of [Market Harborough](/Market_Harborough_railway_station). On 26 June 1885, a new deviation was opened, specifically designed to eliminate the flat crossing of the [Rugby and Stamford Railway](/Rugby_and_Stamford_Railway). Such were the intricate, often costly, efforts required to smooth out the inevitable wrinkles in an ever-expanding railway empire.

#### Northernmost sections

The northern reaches of the [Midland Main Line](/Midland_Main_Line) have a history as convoluted as a poorly laid track switch. The grand ambitions of the [Midland Railway](/Midland_Railway) to construct a direct line from [Derby](/Derby_railway_station) to [Manchester](/Manchester_Central_railway_station) were, rather frustratingly, thwarted in 1863. The culprits? The builders of the [Buxton line](/Buxton_line), who, with a shrewd eye for monopolisation, sought to dominate the lucrative connections to the [West Coast Main Line](/West_Coast_Main_Line), effectively blocking the Midland's direct northern expansion. One might call it a rather unsporting move, but then, business is rarely a gentleman's game.

However, the Midland did achieve a significant northern victory in 1870, when it unveiled a new route from [Chesterfield](/Chesterfield_railway_station) to [Rotherham](/Rotherham_Masborough), a line that, crucially, passed directly through [Sheffield](/Sheffield_railway_station) via the impressive [Bradway Tunnel](/Bradway_Tunnel). This solidified Sheffield's position as a major hub on the Midland's network.

The mid-1870s witnessed a further, rather spectacular, extension of the Midland line northwards. This ambitious undertaking carved a path through the breathtaking, if challenging, landscapes of the [Yorkshire Dales](/Yorkshire_Dales) and the tranquil [Eden Valley](/River_Eden,_Cumbria), forming what is now famously known as the [Settle–Carlisle Railway](/Settle%E2%80%93Carlisle_Railway). A truly epic feat of Victorian engineering, connecting the heart of England to its northernmost reaches.

Before the lamentable closures of the [Beeching era](/Beeching_cuts), the lines leading to [Buxton](/Buxton_railway_station) and those traversing the scenic route via [Millers Dale](/Millers_Dale_railway_station) offered a viable, and indeed competing, primary artery from London to Manchester for many years. These routes proudly hosted celebrated named expresses such as [The Palatine](/The_Palatine) and the sleek, diesel-powered [Blue Pullman](/Blue_Pullman) service (affectionately known as the [Midland Pullman](/Midland_Pullman)), providing a direct, albeit slightly longer, alternative to the established routes. Meanwhile, express trains bound for [Leeds](/Leeds_railway_station) and the distant reaches of [Scotland](/Scotland), including the venerable [Thames–Clyde Express](/Thames%E2%80%93Clyde_Express), predominantly utilised the Midland's parallel [Erewash Valley line](/Erewash_Valley_line), eventually rejoining the main artery before embarking on the magnificent [Settle–Carlisle line](/Settle%E2%80%93Carlisle_Railway). For those heading to [Edinburgh Waverley](/Edinburgh_Waverley_railway_station), services like [The Waverley](/Waverley_(passenger_train)) would traverse through [Corby](/Corby_railway_station) and [Nottingham](/Nottingham_station), painting a vibrant picture of a truly interconnected railway landscape.

#### Under British Railways and privatisation

The march of progress, or perhaps just the relentless grind of change, continued under [British Railways](/British_Railways_Board) and into the era of privatisation. A subtle shift in the operational landscape occurred on 14 April 1958, when the majority of local passenger services between [Leicester](/Leicester_railway_station) and [Nottingham](/Nottingham_station) transitioned to [diesel multiple units](/Diesel_multiple_units). This change streamlined journey times, reducing the inter-city commute to a respectable 51 minutes—a minor detail, perhaps, but indicative of the incremental modernisations that constantly reshaped the network.

A truly seismic event for the [Midland Main Line](/Midland_Main_Line) happened in 1966 with the closure of the [Great Central Main Line](/Great_Central_Main_Line). This dramatic truncation immediately elevated the MML to a position of singular importance, making it the *only* direct main line rail link connecting London with the [East Midlands](/East_Midlands) and substantial portions of [South Yorkshire](/South_Yorkshire). It was a reluctant promotion, born of necessity and the removal of a competitor.

The infamous [Beeching cuts](/Beeching_cuts), coupled with the concurrent [electrification](/Railway_electrification_in_Great_Britain) of the [West Coast Main Line](/West_Coast_Main_Line), effectively spelled the end for the marginally longer, but once significant, London-Manchester service that ran via the [Hope Valley Line](/Hope_Valley_Line) and [Sheffield](/Sheffield_railway_station). The era of competitive inter-city routes was, for a time, largely over, replaced by a more streamlined, though arguably less romantic, network.

In 1977, the [Parliamentary Select Committee on Nationalised Industries](/Parliamentary_Select_Committee_on_Nationalised_Industries) rather boldly recommended that the [electrification of more of Britain's rail network](/Railway_electrification_in_Great_Britain) be seriously considered. By 1979, [British Rail](/British_Railways_Board) (BR) had, with typical bureaucratic efficiency, presented a range of options. Among these was the ambitious, if ultimately deferred, proposal to electrify the [Midland Main Line](/Midland_Main_Line) from London all the way to [Yorkshire](/Yorkshire_and_the_Humber) by the turn of the millennium. A nice thought, perhaps, but one that largely remained on paper. By 1983, only the section from [Moorgate](/Moorgate_railway_station) to [Bedford](/Bedford_railway_station) had seen the tangible benefits of electrification; grander proposals to extend the overhead lines to [Nottingham](/Nottingham_station) and [Sheffield](/Sheffield_railway_station) were, regrettably, not implemented. Some things, it seems, are simply too good to be true, or too expensive to countenance.

The introduction of the iconic [High Speed Train](/InterCity_125) (HST), affectionately known as the InterCity 125, in May 1983, following a crucial resignalling project in the [Leicester](/Leicester_railway_station) area, marked a significant improvement. This allowed the ruling line speed on the fast lines to be increased from a respectable 90 miles per hour (145&#160;km/h) to a more exhilarating 110 miles per hour (177&#160;km/h). A welcome, if still diesel-powered, injection of speed.

Between 2001 and 2003, the section of the line between [Derby](/Derby_railway_station) and [Sheffield](/Sheffield_railway_station) received its own upgrade, with speeds incrementally improved from 100 miles per hour (161&#160;km/h) to 110 miles per hour (177&#160;km/h). This was part of a broader initiative known as Operation Princess, a [Network Rail](/Network_Rail)-funded endeavour to enhance the [Cross Country Route](/Cross_Country_Route). Small victories, but victories nonetheless.

In January 2009, a rather practical addition to the line appeared: a new station, [East Midlands Parkway](/East_Midlands_Parkway_railway_station), strategically located between [Loughborough](/Loughborough_railway_station) and [Trent Junction](/Trent_Junction). Its purpose was clear: to serve as a convenient [park-and-ride](/Park-and-ride) facility for commuters from the surrounding East Midlands cities and, rather more significantly, to provide a rail link to the nearby [East Midlands Airport](/East_Midlands_Airport). A nod to modern travel habits, though one might wonder if passengers truly appreciate the subtle irony of a "parkway" station.

Since then, the line has seen further incremental improvements, with 125 miles per hour (201&#160;km/h) running now permitted on extended stretches. These enhancements have been bolstered by upgraded signalling, an increase in the number of available tracks in certain sections, and the somewhat cyclical revival of proposals to extend electrification beyond [Bedford](/Bedford_railway_station) all the way to [Sheffield](/Sheffield_railway_station). A significant portion of this £70&#160;million upgrade, including some of the line speed increases, became operational on 9 December 2013, a date that probably passed without much fanfare but represented years of planning. More recently, as of April 2025, the line has indeed seen [electrification](/Railway_electrification) extended from [London St Pancras](/London_St_Pancras) to [Wigston South Junction](/Wigston), just south of [Leicester](/Leicester_railway_station). It's a start, one supposes, a glimmer of the fully electric future that's always just over the horizon.

#### Network Rail route strategy for freight (2007)

In 2007, [Network Rail](/Network_Rail), with its characteristic foresight (or perhaps just a belated recognition of pressing needs), unveiled a [Route Utilisation Strategy for freight](/Route_Utilisation_Strategy). The plan, a blueprint for the coming years, aimed to significantly enhance the [Birmingham to Peterborough Line](/Birmingham_to_Peterborough_Line), a crucial corridor for goods movement. This involved not only increasing overall capacity through the perpetually busy environs of [Leicester](/Leicester_railway_station) but also a comprehensive remodelling of the complex junctions at [Syston](/Syston_railway_station) and [Wigston](/South_Wigston_railway_station). Because, as anyone who has ever tried to move anything substantial knows, bottlenecks are the bane of efficient logistics, and railways are no exception. The subtle art of keeping the nation's goods moving, often unseen, yet utterly essential.

#### Network Rail 2010 route plan

The relentless growth in traffic levels on the [Midland Main Line](/Midland_Main_Line) has consistently outpaced the national average, a trend predicted to continue its upward trajectory. In 2006, the now-defunct [Strategic Rail Authority](/Strategic_Rail_Authority) (SRA) attempted to address this burgeoning demand by producing a [Route Utilisation Strategy](/Route_Utilisation_Strategy) specifically for the MML. This document proposed various methods for meeting the anticipated increases, a bureaucratic exercise in future-proofing. Not to be outdone, [Network Rail](/Network_Rail) then initiated its own fresh study in February 2008, eventually publishing its findings in February 2010. These plans outlined a series of improvements, a patchwork of interventions designed to keep the line from buckling under its own success.

Following the partial [electrification](/Railway_electrification) of the line, three towns in North Northamptonshire—[Wellingborough](/Wellingborough_railway_station), [Kettering](/Kettering_railway_station), and [Corby](/Corby_railway_station)—now benefit from the EMR Connect service, providing direct, electric-powered access to [London St Pancras](/London_St_Pancras). This is no small thing, especially given that North Northamptonshire is a designated major growth area, with over 7,400 new homes earmarked for construction in [Wellingborough](/Wellingborough_railway_station) and a further 5,500 new residences planned for [Kettering](/Kettering_railway_station). The railway, it seems, is still seen as a vital component of urban expansion, a testament to its enduring, if sometimes unappreciated, utility.

The highlights of the 2010 [Network Rail](/Network_Rail) plan, a veritable shopping list of upgrades, included:

*   **Line Speed Increases and Safety Enhancements:** Considerable efforts were to be dedicated to projects aimed at increasing line speeds, often involving the rather unglamorous but vital task of removing dangerous [foot crossings](/Level_crossing) and replacing them with safer, if less direct, [footbridges](/Footbridge). Because, apparently, people insist on crossing tracks, and it's generally frowned upon.
*   **Freight Capacity Enhancements:** Recognising the critical role of freight in the national economy, plans were detailed for significant capacity enhancements to facilitate the smoother and more frequent movement of goods. Because the trains carrying your Amazon orders don't just materialise.
*   **Route Resignalling:** A comprehensive [resignalling](/Railway_signalling) of the entire route was envisioned, a massive undertaking that was eventually completed in 2016. The culmination of this project meant that all signalling operations across the MML would be centrally controlled from the East Midlands signalling centre in [Derby](/Derby_railway_station), a technological consolidation aimed at improving efficiency and, one hopes, reducing human error.
*   **Station Rebuilding:** The rather ambitious task of rebuilding both [Bedford](/Bedford_railway_station) and [Leicester](/Leicester_railway_station) stations was also on the agenda, presumably to better accommodate the ever-growing throngs of passengers and to modernise aging infrastructure.
*   **Accessibility Enhancements:** A commendable, if long overdue, focus was placed on improving accessibility at a number of key stations by 2015. These included [Elstree & Borehamwood](/Elstree_%26_Borehamwood_railway_station), [Harpenden](/Harpenden_railway_station), [Loughborough](/Loughborough_railway_station), [Long Eaton](/Long_Eaton_railway_station), [Luton](/Luton_railway_station), and [Wellingborough](/Wellingborough_railway_station). Because everyone, even those with limited mobility, deserves the dubious pleasure of navigating a railway station.
*   **Upgraded Approach Signalling:** The installation of upgraded [approach signalling](/UK_railway_signalling) (specifically, flashing yellow aspects) was planned for critical junctions such as [Radlett](/Radlett_railway_station), [Harpenden](/Harpenden_railway_station), and [Leagrave](/Leagrave_railway_station). This technical improvement was intended to allow trains to traverse these junctions at higher speeds, shaving precious seconds off journey times.
*   **Platform Lengthening:** Platforms at [Wellingborough](/Wellingborough_railway_station), [Kettering](/Kettering_railway_station), [Market Harborough](/Market_Harborough_railway_station), [Loughborough](/Loughborough_railway_station), [Long Eaton](/Long_Eaton_railway_station), and [Beeston](/Beeston_railway_station) stations were scheduled for lengthening. This, alongside work related to the [Thameslink Programme](/Thameslink_Programme) (a beast unto itself), aimed to accommodate longer trains and thus more passengers.
*   **Market Harborough Track Realignment:** A particularly specific improvement involved the realignment of the track and the construction of new platforms at [Market Harborough](/Market_Harborough_railway_station) station. The goal was to increase the permissible speed through the station from a rather sedate 60&#160;mph to a more respectable 85&#160;mph, supposedly saving passengers a monumental 30–60 seconds. One must question if such micro-efficiencies truly justify the monumental effort.
*   **Electrification (again):** The perennial promise of [electrification](/Railway_electrification) was, of course, a major component, a light at the end of a very long, very diesel-fumed tunnel.
*   **Kettering to Oakham Redoubling:** The plan also included the redoubling of the [Kettering to Oakham line](/Oakham%E2%80%93Kettering_line) between [Kettering North Junction](/Kettering_railway_station) and [Corby](/Corby_railway_station), alongside resignalling to [Syston Junction](/Syston_railway_station) via [Oakham](/Oakham_railway_station). This was intended to enable a half-hourly London to Corby passenger service (from an infrastructure perspective, at least) from December 2017, and to create additional paths for crucial rail freight. Because, sometimes, two tracks are simply better than one.

#### Thameslink Programme

The [Thameslink Programme](/Thameslink_Programme), a vast and often bewildering undertaking, has had a profound impact on the southern reaches of the [Midland Main Line](/Midland_Main_Line). A key component of this gargantuan project involved lengthening the platforms at most stations south of [Bedford](/Bedford_railway_station) to accommodate 12-car train formations. This was a necessary step to increase capacity and prepare for the influx of new, longer trains. Happily, [St Pancras](/St_Pancras_railway_station), [Cricklewood](/Cricklewood_railway_station), [Hendon](/Hendon_railway_station), and [Luton Airport Parkway](/Luton_Airport_Parkway_railway_station) were already sufficiently long, spared the indignity of further construction.

However, the laws of physics, or perhaps just the stubborn realities of Victorian engineering, intervened at [Kentish Town](/Kentish_Town_railway_station). Here, existing bridges impose an immovable constraint, meaning the station cannot expand beyond its current 8-car platform length. A minor inconvenience in the grand scheme, but one that highlights the constant battle against historical limitations. Meanwhile, [West Hampstead Thameslink](/West_Hampstead_Thameslink_railway_station) received a shiny new footbridge and a modern station building, a small piece of architectural renewal in a sea of upgrades. In September 2014, the existing Thameslink Great Northern franchise was awarded, and services along this route are now operated by [Govia Thameslink Railway](/Govia_Thameslink_Railway). The network further expanded its reach in 2018, when some [Southern](/Southern_(train_operating_company)) services were, for better or worse, integrated into the larger Thameslink web, creating an even more interconnected, and occasionally bewildering, tapestry of rail services.

#### Station improvements

The stations along the [Midland Main Line](/Midland_Main_Line), like venerable old buildings, are in a constant state of refurbishment or, at the very least, consideration for it. In 2013/14, [Nottingham](/Nottingham_railway_station) station underwent a significant refurbishment, which included a rather necessary restructuring of its platforms. Because, as passenger numbers swell, what once worked often simply... doesn't.

As part of the broader Stanton Cross development, plans are afoot to expand [Wellingborough](/Wellingborough_railway_station) station. One can only hope this expansion is more timely than some other projects. In a rare moment of new construction, [Ilkeston](/Ilkeston_railway_station) station, nestled between [Nottingham](/Nottingham_railway_station) and [Langley Mill](/Langley_Mill_railway_station), was finally opened on 2 April 2017, a testament to the enduring, if slow, demand for local rail connections.

Looking to the future, two new stations were firmly on the drawing board, though their actual manifestation seems to follow a somewhat flexible timeline:

*   **[Brent Cross West](/Brent_Cross_West_railway_station):** Positioned between [Cricklewood](/Cricklewood_railway_station) and [Hendon](/Hendon_railway_station), this station is an integral part of the sprawling [Brent Cross Cricklewood](/Brent_Cross_Cricklewood) development in North London. It finally opened its doors in December 2023, offering a new access point to the network.
*   **[Wixams](/Wixams_railway_station):** Intended to serve a new town situated between [Flitwick](/Flitwick_railway_station) and [Bedford](/Bedford_railway_station), the construction of [Wixams](/Wixams_railway_station) has been, shall we say, repeatedly postponed. Initially anticipated by 2015, then pushed to 2019, the government, with a rather grand pronouncement, confirmed in April 2025 that main construction would finally begin in 2026. This, rather conveniently, is slated to coincide with the nearby [Universal United Kingdom](/Universal_United_Kingdom) Theme Park. One suspects the theme park might be the real catalyst. Groundwork, however, had already commenced by late 2024, proving that sometimes, even bureaucracy can be outpaced by the sheer force of earthmoving equipment.

Beyond these definite (eventually) additions, several other new stations have been proposed, lingering in that tantalising space between aspiration and reality:

*   **[Clay Cross](/Clay_Cross):** A potential new stop between [Chesterfield](/Chesterfield_railway_station) and the Ambergate/[Alfreton](/Alfreton_railway_station) area.
*   **[Irchester](/Irchester) ([Rushden Parkway](/Rushden_Parkway_railway_station)):** Envisioned between [Wellingborough](/Wellingborough_railway_station) and [Bedford](/Bedford_railway_station), this would serve a growing regional need.
*   **[Ampthill](/Ampthill):** Another proposed station, nestled between [Bedford](/Bedford_railway_station) and [Flitwick](/Flitwick_railway_station), aiming to enhance local connectivity.

These proposals, like many in the railway world, serve as a constant reminder that the network is never truly "finished," merely in a perpetual state of becoming, or at least, being discussed.

#### Extension of electrification

Ah, [electrification](/Proposed_railway_electrification_in_Great_Britain), the railway equivalent of a mythical beast: often spoken of, rarely seen in its complete form. Unlike its more fortunate cousins, the [West](/West_Coast_Main_Line) and [East Coast Main Lines](/East_Coast_Main_Line), the [Midland Main Line](/Midland_Main_Line) has historically lacked full overhead [electrification](/Railway_electrification). The line was only electrified as far as [Bedford](/Bedford_railway_station) in the early 1980s, leaving services beyond that point to rely on the venerable, if less environmentally friendly, diesel traction. A constant reminder of what could be, if only the political will (and the funding) were consistently present.

In 2011, work finally commenced on extending this vital electrification, with the ambitious goal of reaching both [Corby](/Corby_railway_station) and [Nottingham](/Nottingham_station). However, as is often the case with grand infrastructure projects, escalating costs led to an initial truncation of these plans, with electrification terminating somewhat prematurely at [Kettering](/Kettering_railway_station) in 2017. A familiar tale of ambition meeting fiscal reality.

But the beast, it seems, was merely resting. In 2021, work commendably recommenced on extending electrification to [Market Harborough](/Market_Harborough_railway_station) and, crucially, onwards to [Wigston](/Wigston). The long-term plan, ever present in the background, is to eventually extend this vital upgrade all the way to [Sheffield](/Sheffield_railway_station). The section to [Wigston](/Wigston) was energised on 28 July 2024, a notable milestone, and completed its testing phase in April 2025. A slow, but persistent, march towards a greener future.

In May 2022, a briefing was released to contractors, a prelude to an invitation to tender for the next phase of the [Midland Main Line Electrification project](/Midland_Main_Line_railway_upgrade). This next, even more ambitious, phase aims to finally extend electrification to [Nottingham](/Nottingham_station) and [Sheffield](/Sheffield_railway_station), a scheme currently projected to cost a rather staggering £1.3&#160;billion. One can only hope that this time, the political will remains steadfast.

Alas, the fickle finger of fate (or perhaps just shifting government priorities) intervened yet again. In July 2025, the [Department for Transport](/Department_for_Transport) announced that plans for further electrification were, rather predictably, put on hold indefinitely. A familiar refrain in the saga of British rail infrastructure, leaving one to wonder if the mythical beast will ever truly be caught.

#### 2021 Integrated Rail Plan

In November 2021, the Government, with a flourish of policy, unveiled its [Integrated Rail Plan for the North and Midlands](/Integrated_Rail_Plan_for_the_North_and_Midlands). This document, a grand vision for the future of rail in these regions, included several significant proposals specifically impacting the [Midland Main Line](/Midland_Main_Line). Among these were a firm commitment to finally complete the stalled electrification work – a promise that, by now, feels like a recurring dream – and an upgrade to modern digital signalling, which, one hopes, will bring the line firmly into the 21st century.

Perhaps the most intriguing proposal was a new connection to [High Speed 2](/High_Speed_2) (HS2). This revised plan envisioned a junction being constructed south of [East Midlands Parkway](/East_Midlands_Parkway_railway_station), a departure from the earlier proposal for an [East Midlands Hub](/East_Midlands_Hub) located further north on the [Toton](/Toton) sidings. The rationale behind this change was to allow HS2 services to connect directly to both [Derby](/Derby_railway_station) and [Nottingham](/Nottingham_station) city centres, utilising the existing MML for access. This was a direct response to a significant criticism of the previous HS2 eastern leg proposal, which had been accused of bypassing these key cities. It seems even grand visions must occasionally bend to the practicalities of local connectivity.

### Route definition

The very term "[Midland Main Line](/Midland_Main_Line)" has a history as circuitous as some of its older track sections. From the late 1840s onwards, it was a rather fluid designation, used to describe any route operated by the [Midland Railway](/Midland_Railway) that was considered significant enough to carry express trains. A somewhat informal, if understandable, classification.

Its first recorded appearance in print, lending it a certain official gravitas, was in [Bradshaw's Guide](/Bradshaw%27s_Guide) of 1848, a publication that, in its day, was the bible for any self-respecting railway traveller. By 1849, the term had clearly gained traction, beginning to be mentioned regularly in local newspapers such as the [Derby Mercury](/Derby_Mercury), indicating its growing recognition in the public consciousness.

In 1867, the [Birmingham Journal](/Birmingham_Journal_(nineteenth_century)) employed the term specifically to describe the new, impressive railway line that was being constructed to run directly into the magnificent [St Pancras](/St_Pancras_railway_station) station. This marked a significant narrowing of its definition, aligning it with the grand southern extension. A year later, in 1868, the term was also used to delineate the [Midland Railway](/Midland_Railway)'s primary north-south artery through [Sheffield](/Sheffield_railway_station), and even extended to routes heading towards [Manchester](/Manchester_Central_railway_station), [Leeds](/Leeds_railway_station), and [Carlisle](/Carlisle_railway_station). It was, in essence, a brand, a mark of the Midland's premier services.

However, under the bureaucratic umbrella of [British Rail](/British_Railways_Board), the term was more rigidly defined, specifically referring to the route between [St Pancras](/St_Pancras_railway_station) and [Sheffield](/Sheffield_railway_station). Since then, [Network Rail](/Network_Rail) has further tightened this definition, restricting its official description of Route 19 to encompass only the lines spanning between [St Pancras](/London_St_Pancras) and [Chesterfield](/Chesterfield_railway_station). A rather precise, if somewhat less romantic, delineation for a line with such a storied past.

### Accidents

Even the most meticulously planned and maintained railway lines are, regrettably, not immune to the occasional, often tragic, incident. The [Midland Main Line](/Midland_Main_Line) has, over its long history, seen its share of such events, each a stark reminder of the inherent risks involved in rapid transit.

*   **26 September 1860: [Bull bridge accident](/Bull_bridge_accident);** A bridge collapse, a structural failure that must have sent shivers down the spine of Victorian engineers.
*   **2 September 1861: [Kentish Town rail accident](/Kentish_Town_rail_accident);** A collision, a harsh lesson in the complexities of coordinating multiple movements on a busy network.
*   **2 September 1898: [Wellingborough rail accident](/Wellingborough_rail_accident);** A derailment, caused by the rather inexplicable presence of a post trolley on the track. One wonders about the story behind that particular piece of debris.
*   **24 December 1910: [Hawes Junction rail crash](/Hawes_Junction_rail_crash);** A signalman, in a moment of tragic human fallibility, simply forgot about a train. A stark reminder that even the most advanced systems are only as reliable as the humans operating them.
*   **2 September 1913: [Ais Gill rail accident](/1913_Ais_Gill_rail_accident);** Another collision, underscoring the dangers of the era's operating practices and the relentless pressures on railway staff.
*   **3 December 1923: [Nunnery Colliery](/Nunnery_Colliery);** While the specifics are not detailed, a colliery incident on a railway line often points to the hazardous interplay between industrial operations and rail transport.
*   **13 December 1926: [Orgreave Paddy Mail accident](/Orgreave_Paddy_Mail_accident);** An accident involving a "Paddy Mail" train, typically used for transporting miners, highlighting the specific dangers faced by industrial workers travelling by rail.
*   **1 February 2008: [Barrow upon Soar rail accident](/Barrow_upon_Soar_train_crash);** A more recent incident, reminding us that vigilance is a constant requirement, even in the modern age.

Each of these events, separated by decades, represents a moment of failure, a point where the intricate dance of steel and steam, or later, diesel and electricity, went tragically awry. They are the grim footnotes in the otherwise triumphant narrative of railway progress.

### Train operating companies

The modern [Midland Main Line](/Midland_Main_Line) is not run by a single, monolithic entity, but rather a collection of train operating companies, each with its own niche and responsibilities. It's a rather fragmented affair, a testament to the wonders (or frustrations) of privatisation.

#### East Midlands Railway

The primary orchestrator of services on the [Midland Main Line](/Midland_Main_Line) is [East Midlands Railway](/East_Midlands_Railway) (EMR). This company runs a rather impressive four [InterCity](/Inter-city_rail) trains every hour from [London St Pancras](/London_St_Pancras), with services neatly split: two trains per hour heading north to [Nottingham](/Nottingham_station) and two trains per hour destined for [Sheffield](/Sheffield_railway_station). For these flagship InterCity services, EMR relies on its fleet of [Class 222 Meridian](/British_Rail_Class_222) trains, deployed in various carriage formations to match demand. They're quite capable, for a diesel-electric hybrid.

Beyond the long-distance expresses, EMR also operates a more frequent, twice-hourly commuter service from [London St Pancras](/London_St_Pancras) to [Corby](/Corby_railway_station). This particular offering is branded as EMR Connect, a rather direct name for a service that utilises [Class 360 Desiro](/Class_360) [electric multiple units](/Electric_multiple_units). It provides a crucial, rapid link for commuters in the newly electrified sections, a small but significant step towards a more modern railway.

#### Govia Thameslink Railway

Further south, particularly below [Bedford](/Bedford_railway_station), the [Midland Main Line](/Midland_Main_Line) becomes an integral part of the sprawling [Thameslink network](/Thameslink_(route)), operated by [Govia Thameslink Railway](/Govia_Thameslink_Railway). This operator provides frequent, indeed 24-hour, services along its designated route, connecting the MML to destinations further afield such as [London Bridge](/London_Bridge_railway_station), [Gatwick Airport](/Gatwick_Airport_railway_station), the coastal delights of [Brighton](/Brighton_railway_station), and the suburban reaches of [Sutton](/Sutton_railway_station_(London)). For these extensive services, GTR deploys its modern fleet of 8- and 12-car [Class 700](/British_Rail_Class_700) [electric multiple units](/Electric_multiple_units), a testament to the sheer scale and complexity of urban rail transport in the capital's orbit.

#### CrossCountry

The [CrossCountry](/CrossCountry) franchise, as its name rather helpfully suggests, specialises in services that span the length and breadth of the country. On the [Midland Main Line](/Midland_Main_Line), it operates an hourly service between [Derby](/Derby_railway_station) and [Sheffield](/Sheffield_railway_station), forming a vital link in its broader route connecting the South West and North East of England. Additionally, CrossCountry provides a twice-hourly service between [Nottingham](/Nottingham_station) and [Derby](/Derby_railway_station), with these trains continuing onwards to the bustling interchange at [Birmingham New Street](/Birmingham_New_Street_railway_station) and, for some, as far as [Cardiff Central](/Cardiff_Central_railway_station). It's a network that, by its very nature, weaves together disparate regions, though sometimes with a certain, shall we say, 'efficiency' of connections.

#### Northern Trains

Serving the northern stretches of the network, [Northern Trains](/Northern_Trains) contributes its own hourly service from [Leeds](/Leeds_railway_station) to [Nottingham](/Nottingham_station). This route, a regional lifeline, meanders through [Barnsley](/Barnsley_railway_station) and [Alfreton](/Alfreton_railway_station), connecting smaller communities and providing essential local links that often go unnoticed amidst the grander pronouncements of inter-city travel.

#### TransPennine Express

Finally, [TransPennine Express](/TransPennine_Express) also makes an appearance in the [Sheffield](/Sheffield_railway_station) area. Its services connect [Liverpool Lime Street](/Liverpool_Lime_Street_railway_station) to the rather more distant coastal town of [Cleethorpes](/Cleethorpes_railway_station), utilising a segment of the [Midland Main Line](/Midland_Main_Line) to bridge the gap between these two distinct regions. It's a reminder that the MML, while a distinct entity, is also a crucial component of a much larger, interconnected rail tapestry.

### Route description

The [Midland Main Line](/Midland_Main_Line) traverses a fascinating array of cities, towns, and villages, each contributing its own unique flavour to the journey. Below is a somewhat comprehensive (and perhaps exhausting) rundown of the places served by this venerable line, with stations of particular prominence, indicated by their high usage, appearing in bold. This description also, rather grandly, includes the historical extensions that once reached all the way to [Manchester](/Manchester_Central_railway_station) (where it seamlessly linked with the [West Coast Main Line](/West_Coast_Main_Line)) and, even further north, to [Carlisle](/Carlisle_railway_station) (via [Leeds](/Leeds_railway_station), where it met the [East Coast Main Line](/East_Coast_Main_Line)). A testament to the Midland's once-expansive ambitions.

[Network Rail](/Network_Rail), in its infinite wisdom, categorises all lines within the [East Midlands](/East_Midlands) and the route extending northwards as far as [Chesterfield](/Chesterfield_railway_station) and southwards to London as 'Route 19'. However, the actual physical line, in its glorious complexity, stretches beyond this administrative boundary, delving into the realms of routes 10 and 11. Because, as always, reality rarely conforms perfectly to bureaucratic neatness.

#### London to Nottingham and Sheffield (Network Rail Route 19)

The journey begins (or ends, depending on your direction of travel) in the heart of the capital, at [London St Pancras](/London_St_Pancras), a station that opened in 1868 and now boasts a rather impressive 15 platforms, handling a staggering 31.724 million passengers in 2015/16. Just north of this grand terminus, the high-speed marvel that is [High Speed 1](/High_Speed_1) gracefully diverges.

The line then proceeds through [Kentish Town](/Kentish_Town_station), a London locale that saw its station open in 1868. With 4 platforms, it served 2.844 million passengers in the same period. Just north of the station, a branch from the [Gospel Oak to Barking line](/Gospel_Oak_to_Barking_line) joins the main artery.

Next is [West Hampstead Thameslink](/West_Hampstead_Thameslink_railway_station), opening in 1871, providing 4 platforms for 3.710 million passengers. Then comes [Cricklewood](/Cricklewood_railway_station), a 1868 station with 4 platforms, handling 1.057 million passengers. North of Cricklewood, the [Dudding Hill Line](/Dudding_Hill_Line) diverges.

A newer addition is [Brent Cross West](/Brent_Cross_West_railway_station), opened in 2023 in [Brent Cross](/Brent_Cross), London, also with 4 platforms. The [Dudding Hill Line](/Dudding_Hill_Line) diverges again, this time south of Brent Cross.

Continuing north, we reach [Hendon](/Hendon_railway_station), a 1868 station with 4 platforms and 1.178 million passengers. [Mill Hill Broadway](/Mill_Hill_Broadway_railway_station), also from 1868, in [Mill Hill](/Mill_Hill), London ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) TQ213918), offers 4 platforms to 1.949 million users.

[Elstree & Borehamwood](/Elstree_%26_Borehamwood_railway_station), in [Borehamwood](/Borehamwood), [Hertfordshire](/Hertfordshire), opened in 1868, has 4 platforms and served 3.382 million passengers. [Radlett](/Radlett_railway_station), also 1868, in [Radlett](/Radlett), Hertfordshire ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) TQ164998), provides 4 platforms for 1.188 million.

The historic city of [St Albans](/St_Albans) hosts [St Albans City](/St_Albans_City_railway_station), a 1868 station ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) TL155070) with 4 platforms and a substantial 7.451 million passengers. [Harpenden](/Harpenden_railway_station), in [Harpenden](/Harpenden), Hertfordshire ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) TL137142), opened in 1868, has 4 platforms and 3.337 million users.

Moving into [Bedfordshire](/Bedfordshire), we find [Luton Airport Parkway](/Luton_Airport_Parkway_railway_station) in [Luton](/Luton) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) TL105205). A relatively modern addition, opened in 1999, it has 4 platforms and served 3.188 million passengers, a testament to the ever-increasing demand for airport connectivity. The main [Luton](/Luton_railway_station) station, opened in 1868 ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) TL092216), boasts 5 platforms and 3.626 million passengers.

[Leagrave](/Leagrave_railway_station), in [Leagrave](/Leagrave), Luton, Bedfordshire ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) TL061241), opened in 1868, has 4 platforms and 1.915 million users. [Harlington](/Harlington_railway_station), in [Harlington,_Bedfordshire](/Harlington,_Bedfordshire) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) TL034303), opened in 1868, provides 4 platforms for a more modest 0.336 million.

[Flitwick](/Flitwick_railway_station), in [Flitwick](/Flitwick), Bedfordshire ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) TL034350), opened in 1870, has 4 platforms and 1.480 million passengers. Finally, [Bedford](/Bedford_railway_station) Midland, in [Bedford](/Bedford), Bedfordshire ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) TL041497), opened in 1859, is a significant hub with 5 platforms and 3.830 million passengers. South of Bedford, the [Marston Vale line](/Marston_Vale_line) diverges.

Crossing into [Northamptonshire](/Northamptonshire), we arrive at [Wellingborough](/Wellingborough_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SP903681), opened in 1857, with 4 platforms and 0.969 million passengers. [Kettering](/Kettering_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SP863780), also from 1857, has 4 platforms and 1.042 million users. North of Kettering, at Glendon Junction, the [Oakham–Kettering line](/Oakham%E2%80%93Kettering_line) diverges.

**Via Corby & diversion route:**
This alternative route takes us to [Corby](/Corby_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SP891886), a modern station opened in 2009, with 1 platform serving 0.278 million passengers, forming part of the [Oakham–Kettering line](/Oakham%E2%80%93Kettering_line). Further along, [Oakham](/Oakham_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SK856090), in [Rutland](/Rutland), opened in 1848, has 2 platforms and 0.213 million users, connecting to the [Birmingham–Peterborough line](/Birmingham%E2%20Peterborough_line). The route then reaches [Melton Mowbray](/Melton_Mowbray_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SK752187), in [Leicestershire](/Leicestershire), opened in 1848, with 2 platforms and 0.266 million passengers.

**Main Line via Market Harborough:**
Returning to the main line, we arrive at [Market Harborough](/Market_Harborough_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SP741874), in [Leicestershire](/Leicestershire), opened in 1850, with 2 platforms and 0.870 million passengers.
Then, the bustling hub of [Leicester](/Leicester_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SK593041), in Leicestershire, opened in 1840, a major station with 4 platforms and a substantial 5.247 million passengers. South of Leicester, at Wigston Junction, the [Birmingham to Peterborough Line](/Birmingham_to_Peterborough_Line) diverges.

Continuing north, [Syston](/Syston_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SK621111), in Leicestershire, opened in 1994, has 1 platform and 0.210 million users. North of Syston, the [Birmingham to Peterborough Line](/Birmingham_to_Peterborough_Line) diverges once more. [Sileby](/Sileby_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SK602151), in Leicestershire, opened in 1994, has 2 platforms and 0.123 million.

[Barrow-upon-Soar](/Barrow-upon-Soar_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SK577172), in Leicestershire, opened in 1994, has 2 platforms and 0.098 million. Then, [Loughborough](/Loughborough_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SK543204), in Leicestershire, opened in 1872, with 3 platforms and 1.298 million passengers.

Finally, [East Midlands Parkway](/East_Midlands_Parkway_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SK496296), in [Ratcliffe-on-Soar](/Ratcliffe-on-Soar), [Nottinghamshire](/Nottinghamshire) (serving [East Midlands Airport](/East_Midlands_Airport)), opened in 2007, has 4 platforms and 0.306 million users. North of East Midlands Parkway, the route splits into three vital branches: the original line to Clay Cross Junction via [Derby](/Derby_railway_station), the [Nottingham](/Nottingham_station) branch, and the [Erewash Valley Line](/Erewash_Valley_Line).

**Via Derby:**
Following the path to [Derby](/Derby_railway_station), we first encounter [Long Eaton](/Long_Eaton_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SK481321), in [Derbyshire](/Derbyshire), opened in 1888, with 2 platforms and 0.660 million passengers. A cord south of Long Eaton connects to the [Nottingham](/Nottingham_station) branch. [Spondon](/Spondon_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SK397351), in [Spondon](/Spondon), [Derby](/Derby), Derbyshire, opened in 1839, has 2 platforms and a rather meagre 0.026 million users.

The important hub of [Derby](/Derby_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SK362355), in Derbyshire, opened in 1839, is a significant interchange with 6 platforms and 3.767 million passengers. South of Derby, the [Cross Country Route](/Cross_Country_Route) and [Crewe to Derby Line](/Crewe_to_Derby_Line) diverge. [Duffield](/Duffield_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SK345435), in [Duffield,_Derbyshire](/Duffield,_Derbyshire), opened in 1841, has 3 platforms and 0.061 million.

[Belper](/Belper_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SK348475), in [Belper](/Belper), Derbyshire, opened in 1840, has 2 platforms and 0.225 million users. Finally, [Ambergate](/Ambergate_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SK348516), in Ambergate, Derbyshire, opened in 1840, has 1 platform and 0.042 million. At [Ambergate Junction](/Ambergate_Junction), the [Derwent Valley line](/Derwent_Valley_line) diverges.

**Via Nottingham:**
Taking the branch towards [Nottingham](/Nottingham_station), we find [Attenborough](/Attenborough_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SK518346), in [Attenborough,_Nottinghamshire](/Attenborough,_Nottinghamshire), opened in 1856, with 2 platforms and 0.112 million passengers. [Beeston](/Beeston_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SK533362), in [Beeston,_Nottinghamshire](/Beeston,_Nottinghamshire), opened in 1839, has 2 platforms and 0.574 million users.

The major terminus of [Nottingham](/Nottingham_railway_station) Midland ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SK574392), in [Nottingham](/Nottingham), Nottinghamshire, opened in 1904, is a substantial station with 7 platforms and a significant 7.200 million passengers. Northbound trains here reverse to continue towards [Langley Mill](/Langley_Mill_railway_station), while others proceed onto the [Robin Hood Line](/Robin_Hood_Line), [Grantham line](/Nottingham%E2%80%93Grantham_line), or [Lincoln line](/Nottingham%E2%80%93Lincoln_line).

**Via Erewash Valley (bypassing or calling at Nottingham):**
This alternative route takes us through [Ilkeston](/Ilkeston_railway_station), in [Ilkeston](/Ilkeston), Derbyshire, a more recent addition opened in 2017, with 2 platforms. Then, [Langley Mill](/Langley_Mill_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SK449470), in [Langley Mill](/Langley_Mill), Derbyshire, opened in 1847, has 2 platforms and 0.116 million users. South of Langley Mill, the Erewash Valley and Trent Nottingham lines conveniently rejoin. Finally, [Alfreton](/Alfreton_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SK422561), in [Alfreton](/Alfreton), Derbyshire, opened in 1862, has 2 platforms and 0.283 million passengers.

**Clay Cross Junction to Leeds:**
From Clay Cross Junction, the line continues towards [Leeds](/Leeds_railway_station). First, [Chesterfield](/Chesterfield_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SK388714), in [Chesterfield,_Derbyshire](/Chesterfield,_Derbyshire), opened in 1840, has 3 platforms and 1.731 million passengers. South of Chesterfield, the various lines from Trent Junction via [Derby](/Derby_railway_station) and the Erewash Valley converge.

[Dronfield](/Dronfield_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SK354784), in [Dronfield](/Dronfield), Derbyshire, opened in 1981, has 2 platforms and 0.200 million users. North of Dronfield, the [Hope Valley Line](/Hope_Valley_Line) diverges.

The major northern hub of [Sheffield](/Sheffield_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SK358869), in [South Yorkshire](/South_Yorkshire), opened in 1870, is a vast station with 9 platforms and a colossal 9.213 million passengers. South of Sheffield, the [Hope Valley Line](/Hope_Valley_Line) diverges, and north of Sheffield, the [Sheffield to Lincoln Line](/Sheffield_to_Lincoln_Line) also branches off.

[Meadowhall Interchange](/Meadowhall_Interchange) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SK390912), in [Sheffield](/Sheffield), South Yorkshire, opened in 1990, has 4 platforms and 2.138 million users. At Meadowhall, the [Hallam](/Hallam_Line) and [Penistone Lines](/Penistone_Line) diverge.

**Via Doncaster:**
An alternative route heads through [Doncaster](/Doncaster_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SE571032), in [Doncaster](/Doncaster), South Yorkshire, opened in 1838, a large station with 8 platforms and 3.752 million passengers. South of Doncaster, it connects to the [East Coast Main Line](/East_Coast_Main_Line).

**Bypassing Doncaster:**
For those bypassing Doncaster, the line reaches [Wakefield Westgate](/Wakefield_Westgate_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SE327207), in [Wakefield](/Wakefield), [West Yorkshire](/West_Yorkshire), opened in 1867, with 2 platforms and 2.519 million users. South of Wakefield Westgate, it connects with the [East Coast Main Line](/East_Coast_Main_Line).

Finally, the grand northern terminus of [Leeds](/Leeds_railway_station) ([grid reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SE299331), in [Leeds](/Leeds), West Yorkshire, opened in 1938, is a massive station with 17 platforms, serving an astounding 29.724 million passengers. This is the heart of the Leeds City lines.

