#### Ambergate Junction to Manchester

Once upon a time, in a slightly less fragmented railway era, the complex network of road and rail around [Ambergate Junction](/Ambergate_Junction) was a bustling nexus. It was the crucial point where express trains bound for [Manchester](/Manchester_Central_railway_station) would diverge from the main line, embarking on a journey that was once considered an integral part of the [Midland Main Line](/Midland_Main_Line) itself. However, for the purposes of modern marketing and franchising, this particular limb has been, shall we say, officially disassociated. It is now considered a separate entity, primarily referred to as the [Manchester, Buxton, Matlock and Midlands Junction Railway](/Manchester,_Buxton,_Matlock_and_Midlands_Junction_Railway), or, in its more contemporary guise, the [Derwent Valley line](/Derwent_Valley_line).

In its heyday, this route was a proud carrier of named expresses, such as the rather grandly titled [The Palatine](/The_Palatine). Much later, in the mid-20th century, it played host to the sleek, futuristic (for its time) [Midland Pullman](/Midland_Pullman), a diesel-powered luxury service that offered a glimpse of high-speed travel.

